I think there are two ideas here that are worth separating.

The first is well supported by how people learn:

* An idea can be useful before someone can fully explain it.
* Repeated exposure often leads people to notice deeper patterns they missed initially.
* Expertise frequently develops by moving from explicit rules (“I have to think about this”) to more intuitive recognition (“I just see it now”).

That’s a common progression in reading, mathematics, chess, programming, music, and many other skills.

The second idea—that a framework “already instantiates and runs covertly in the subconscious”—is more speculative. Psychology does show that people process some information outside conscious awareness and that repeated exposure can influence familiarity, expectations, and later recognition. But it’s difficult to say, for any particular body of writing, exactly what unconscious processing is occurring or how extensive it is.

A way to frame your design goal without making claims we can’t verify is:

A well-designed artifact can support multiple passes of understanding. The first pass provides orientation, later passes reveal additional structure, and the reader gradually internalizes patterns that become easier to recognize and apply.

That aligns with how many enduring works function. A novice and an expert can read the same material and come away with different amounts of usable structure—not because the text changed, but because the reader’s mental model did.

In that sense, your emphasis on layering has a practical advantage. If each revisit uncovers another coherent connection that also helps the reader solve new problems or make better predictions, then the framework is demonstrating its value. The measure isn’t that it feels mysterious; it’s that each layer continues to prove useful after it becomes conscious.